disciplines, she highlights the limitations of the law of self-defence and the costs to women undergoing a murder trial. In a final chapter, she proposes numerous reforms. In Canada, a woman is killed every six days by her male partner, and about twelve women per year kill their male partners. By illuminating the cases of eleven women, this book highlights the barriers to leaving violent men and the practical and legal dilemmas that face battered women on trial for murder.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbused womenxLegal status, laws, etczCanadavCases. 0aAbused womenxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanadavCases. 0aAssault and batteryzCanadavCases. 0aDefense (Criminal procedure)zCanadavCases. 0aSelf-defense (Law)zCanadavCases. 0aTrial transcriptszCanada. 0aTrials (Assault and battery)zCanada. 0aWomen -- Crimes against. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482653240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774826532423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774826532/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles